{
  "masechta": "Zevachim",
  "daf": 38,
  "amud": "a-b",
  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "The Debate of Beis Shammai and Beis Hillel on the Corners of the Chatas",
      "display_title": "Beis Shammai vs Hillel",
      "timestamp": "00:12",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Introduction to the debate: two corners (Beis Shammai) versus one corner (Beis Hillel) for the chatas",
          "display_title": "Two vs One Corner",
          "timestamp": "00:12"
        },
        {
          "title": "Beis Shammai's derivation from the word karnos (corners), yielding four lechatechilah and two be'dieved",
          "display_title": "Karnos Derivation",
          "timestamp": "00:28"
        },
        {
          "title": "The struggle to derive Beis Hillel's position of one be'dieved from the counted corners",
          "display_title": "Hillel's Corner Count",
          "timestamp": "00:37"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Baraita's Derivation from Vekiper: Why Three Repetitions are Necessary",
      "display_title": "Vekiper Drasha",
      "timestamp": "00:52",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Introduction of the baraita deriving Beis Hillel's position from vekiper vekiper vekiper (three repetitions of atonement)",
          "display_title": "Three Vekipers",
          "timestamp": "00:52"
        },
        {
          "title": "The logical argument (din) that one application of blood suffices for all other korbanos, potentially replacing the need for a pasuk",
          "display_title": "Logical Sufficiency",
          "timestamp": "02:04"
        },
        {
          "title": "The alternative logical path: comparing the chatas on the outer altar to the chatas on the inner altar",
          "display_title": "Inner vs Outer",
          "timestamp": "03:21"
        },
        {
          "title": "The conclusion that logic is insufficient because one could analogize either way, therefore a pasuk is needed",
          "display_title": "Need for Pasuk",
          "timestamp": "04:36"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Adda bar Ahava's explanation: using vekiper along with veslach to derive decreasing requirements",
          "display_title": "Adda's Explanation",
          "timestamp": "07:10"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Gemara's Examination of Alternative Readings of Vekiper",
      "display_title": "Vekiper Alternatives",
      "timestamp": "08:00",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "First alternative: vekiper could mean even if you only did three above and one below",
          "display_title": "Three Above One Below",
          "timestamp": "08:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rejection: this would eliminate the requirement of four corners entirely, requiring a stronger reading",
          "display_title": "Rejection: Eliminate Cor…",
          "timestamp": "09:38"
        },
        {
          "title": "Second alternative: vekiper could mean even if you did all four below (no corners above)",
          "display_title": "All Below Option",
          "timestamp": "10:31"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's response: three vekipers only get you from four to one; four vekipers would be needed for all below",
          "display_title": "Need Four Vekipers",
          "timestamp": "10:31"
        },
        {
          "title": "Third alternative: vekiper could mean one above and three below",
          "display_title": "One Above Three Below",
          "timestamp": "11:10"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rejection: no korban has blood split between upper and lower halves of the altar as a requirement",
          "display_title": "No Split Placement",
          "timestamp": "11:41"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's proof from Yom Kippur: the High Priest's sprinkling (one above, seven below) is not split placement",
          "display_title": "Yom Kippur Proof",
          "timestamp": "12:55"
        },
        {
          "title": "Raya Yehuda's explanation of matzlif (flicking motion) as determining direction, not altar location",
          "display_title": "Matzlif Meaning",
          "timestamp": "13:21"
        },
        {
          "title": "Application to the golden altar: sprinkling on the taharo (middle/exposed part) of the mizbeach",
          "display_title": "Taharo Sprinkling",
          "timestamp": "13:53"
        },
        {
          "title": "Raba bar Shila's clarification: exposed part is still the roof, hence one place, not split",
          "display_title": "One Place Clarified",
          "timestamp": "15:09"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's exception: all other korbanos have shirayim (remainder) spilled at the yesod, yet still in one place",
          "display_title": "Shirayim Exception",
          "timestamp": "15:36"
        },
        {
          "title": "Discussion of pnimiyim shirayim: inner chatas blood poured at the yesod of the outer altar",
          "display_title": "Pnimiyim Shirayim",
          "timestamp": "16:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "Conclusion: on one mizbeach, blood placement cannot fundamentally require two separate locations",
          "display_title": "One Altar Principle",
          "timestamp": "16:27"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Mishna's Ruling on Pigul and the Machmir/Meikel Status of Beis Shammai and Beis Hillel",
      "display_title": "Pigul Hemshek",
      "timestamp": "17:52",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Baraita of Rabbi Eliezer ben Yaakov: Beis Shammai requires two matanos for chatas, one for other korbanos to be matir and mechugel; Beis Hillel requires one for all",
          "display_title": "Matir and Mefugel",
          "timestamp": "17:52"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Oshaya's challenge: why is Beis Shammai listed as meikel (lenient) here when typically machmir?",
          "display_title": "Oshaya's Challenge",
          "timestamp": "18:57"
        },
        {
          "title": "Analysis: Beis Shammai is machmir for matir (making the korban permitted to eat), but meikel for pigul (spoilage thought)",
          "display_title": "Machmir vs Meikel",
          "timestamp": "19:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "Raba's resolution: the debate was framed from the perspective of what makes the korban muttar (permitted), not pigul",
          "display_title": "Raba's Resolution",
          "timestamp": "20:04"
        },
        {
          "title": "Tosafot's question: how do we know Beis Shammai requires pigul thought at both matanos (not either one)?",
          "display_title": "Pigul Requirement",
          "timestamp": "21:05"
        },
        {
          "title": "Possible scenarios where Beis Shammai is meikel by pigul even if requiring both matanos",
          "display_title": "Shammai Meikel Cases",
          "timestamp": "21:15"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
